"content": "MARCH Assessment — Severely Injured Child, Field Trauma Protocol\\n\\nMARCH is the military/tactical trauma sequence, adapted for pediatric field use.\\nPriority order differs from ABCDE — hemorrhage control comes before airway in polytrauma.\\n\\nM — MASSIVE HEMORRHAGE \(First Priority\):\\n  Look: Visible blood pooling, saturated clothing\\n  Act: Tourniquet for extremity hemorrhage \(2–3 inches above wound\)\\n  Wound packing with hemostatic gauze for junctional wounds\\n  Pressure dressings\\n  Do NOT proceed to A until massive bleeding is controlled\\n\\nA — AIRWAY:\\n  Assess: Is the airway open? Is child making sounds?\\n  Child-specific: Head-tilt chin-lift — avoid over-extension in infants \(neutral position\)\\n  Jaw thrust if spinal injury possible\\n  OPA if unconscious without gag reflex\\n  Position: Jaw up, airway opening\\n  Suction if available\\n\\nR — RESPIRATION:\\n  Rate, depth, symmetry, effort\\n  Open pneumothorax: 3-sided chest seal\\n  Tension pneumothorax: Needle decompression\\n  Oxygen if available\\n  Bag-valve mask if inadequate\\n\\nC — CIRCULATION:\\n  HR: Tachycardia = compensated shock in children\\n  Capillary refill <2 seconds = adequate\\n  Skin: Pale, mottled, cold = shock\\n  IV/IO access → 20 mL/kg NS bolus if shock signs present\\n  Reassess after each bolus\\n\\nH — HYPOTHERMIA PREVENTION:\\n  Pediatric patients lose heat rapidly — especially if wet or exposed\\n  Remove wet clothing\\n  Cover with mylar/thermal blanket — include head\\n  Warm IV fluids if possible\\n  Ground insulation — never lay child on bare cold ground\\n\\nReassess MARCH After Every Intervention — document findings for handoff team."}]}
